    50 => [ // saphala
        'slug' => 'saphala',
        'history' => 'Saphala Ekadashi falls during the Krishna Paksha of the Pausha month (December-January). The name "Saphala" means "fruitful" or "successful." This Ekadashi is described in the Padma Purana, where Lord Krishna narrates its glories to Yudhishthira Maharaja. The story involves King Mahishmati, whose son was cursed by a brahmana to become a demon. The prince lived in a forest, surviving on fruits and roots, and observed this Ekadashi with great devotion. His sincere observance broke the curse, and he regained his human form and kingdom.',
        'significance' => 'Saphala Ekadashi is known for granting the fulfillment of desires and making life truly fruitful. Observing this fast purifies the heart and mind, removing obstacles that prevent spiritual progress. The Padma Purana states that even simple observance of this Ekadashi brings results equal to worshipping the Lord with a thousand sacrifices. It is especially powerful for those seeking success in their endeavors and relief from material difficulties.',
        'benefits' => 'Devotees who observe Saphala Ekadashi with sincerity receive the blessings of Lord Vishnu for success in all undertakings. The fast destroys sins accumulated over many lifetimes and grants material prosperity alongside spiritual advancement. Those who donate food and charity on this day receive manifold returns. The observer is freed from the reactions of sinful activities and progresses toward liberation. Families observe this Ekadashi for overall well-being and harmony.',
