    51 => [ // putrada
        'slug' => 'putrada',
        'history' => 'Pausha Putrada Ekadashi falls during the Krishna Paksha of the Pausha month (December-January). The name means "bestower of sons." This Ekadashi is described in the Brahma Vaivarta Purana, where Lord Krishna explains to Yudhishthira Maharaja the story of a king named Sumedha who had no children despite being righteous. His wife observed this Ekadashi with great devotion and prayed for a child. Pleased by her sincerity, the Lord blessed them with a glorious son who became a great king.',
        'significance' => 'Putrada Ekadashi holds special significance for those desiring children and for the welfare of existing children. In Vedic culture, having children — especially devoted sons — is considered one of the most important responsibilities of grihastha life. This Ekadashi is observed to invoke the blessings of Lord Vishnu for progeny and for the protection and well-being of children. It also signifies the importance of raising children in spiritual consciousness.',
        'benefits' => 'Observing Putrada Ekadashi blesses childless couples with the boon of children. For those who already have children, it ensures their health, wisdom, and spiritual progress. The fast purifies the consciousness of the parents, enabling them to raise their children in a spiritually conducive environment. Donations made on this day — especially to educational institutions and temples — bring lasting merit. The observer is blessed with family happiness and the joy of raising devoted children.',
